  <h2>How to Choose the Right Diligence Method</h2>
  <ol class="steps-list">
    <li>
      <strong>Assess the defender's situation</strong><br>
      Do they have a job? Property? Bank accounts? Assets? Start with the most straightforward method based on what you know.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Start with low-cost methods</strong><br>
      Earnings Arrestment (if employed) or Bank Arrestment (if you know their bank) are usually the best first steps.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Consider the debt amount</strong><br>
      For smaller debts (under ¬£1,000), avoid expensive diligence like Attachment of Goods. For larger debts, Inhibition may be worthwhile even if payment is delayed.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Evaluate likelihood of success</strong><br>
      Don't spend money on diligence if the defender has no assets, income, or ability to pay.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Use multiple methods if necessary</strong><br>
      You can combine methods - e.g., Earnings Arrestment for ongoing recovery plus Inhibition to secure against property.
    </li>
  </ol>

